<methodology slug="pm-tools-overview">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>pm-agile</domain>
    <summary>Framework for PM tool selection using evidence-grounded MoSCoW requirements, hard constraints (cost, compliance, IDP), weighted scoring with sensitivity analysis, and ADR decision templates.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>pm-tools</tag>
      <tag>tool-selection</tag>
      <tag>moscow</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>adr</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="pm-tools-comparison"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>PM Tools Overview</title>

    <summary>A structured framework for selecting the right project management tool based on team size, workflow complexity, compliance requirements, and ecosystem fit. The core rule: anchor every tool selection to a MoSCoW requirements table grounded in stakeholder evidence, then apply hard constraints (price ceiling, data residency, compliance, IDP) to produce a shortlist of 3-5 candidates before evaluating features.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Tool selections driven by executive preference, hype, or feature-list comparisons routinely fail at adoption. Anchoring to documented requirements with verbatim evidence forces rigor and makes the decision defensible during post-mortem reviews. A weighted scorecard with sensitivity analysis reveals when the "winner" is fragile (ranking flips under reasonable weight perturbations).</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new team or project without existing tooling.</item>
        <item>Outgrowing a current PM solution (capacity, compliance, or integrations).</item>
        <item>Consolidating multiple tools across an organization after merger or acquisition.</item>
        <item>Evaluating tools during vendor renewal when pricing model changes.</item>
        <item>Post-acquisition tool standardization requiring a defensible ADR.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-team / solo decision with low switching cost — pick by gut, time-box a 2-week trial, ship.</item>
        <item>Switching tools to escape a process or personnel problem — fix the root cause instead.</item>
        <item>A tool already works with no measurable pain — overhead exceeds value.</item>
        <item>Pre-product-market-fit startups — tool-selection theatre distracts from product.</item>
        <item>Decisions already locked by executive preference or vendor relationship — analysis will not change the outcome.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="quick-reference">
      <p>Tool fit is determined by team size, workflow complexity, ecosystem integration, and compliance posture — not feature counts. "Best for X" labels are directional; always validate against the team's actual MoSCoW requirements.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Jira: enterprise, compliance-heavy, 50+ users. Highly customizable; complex; large ecosystem.</item>
        <item>Linear: engineering-focused, 10-100 users. Fastest UX; keyboard-first; opinionated workflow; GitHub-native.</item>
        <item>ClickUp: all-in-one consolidation, 10-500 users. Most features; some performance issues; steep learning curve.</item>
        <item>Notion: docs + light PM, 5-100 users. Flexible; beautiful; not PM-primary; weak reporting.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects (v2): developers already in GitHub, any size. Free for OSS; GraphQL; limited PM depth.</item>
        <item>GitLab Boards: DevOps-integrated teams, 10-1000 users. Full DevOps platform; Premium for WIP limits.</item>
        <item>Azure DevOps: Microsoft-stack enterprises, 50+ users. Compliance-grade; Entra integration; CMMI support.</item>
        <item>Trello: simple Kanban, 5-50 users. Easy onboarding; limited scaling; good for low-complexity workflows.</item>
        <item>Asana: marketing and ops teams, 10-500 users. Clean UX; goals and portfolios; less dev-focused.</item>
        <item>Monday.com: non-technical teams, 10-500 users. Visual; highly flexible; expensive at scale.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="jira">
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Choose Jira for organizations with 50+ users, complex approval workflows, compliance requirements (SOC2, FedRAMP), or need for extensive plugin ecosystem.</statement>
        <rationale>Jira's value is in customizability and ecosystem breadth. For simpler needs, the UI complexity and performance overhead outweigh the benefits.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using Jira for a team of fewer than 10 with straightforward Kanban needs.</description>
        <reason>Jira's configuration overhead (workflows, schemes, custom fields) creates administrative burden that kills small-team productivity.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="linear">
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Choose Linear for developer-focused teams of 10-100 that prioritize speed, keyboard-driven UX, and tight GitHub integration over flexibility.</statement>
        <rationale>Linear's opinionated design eliminates configuration decisions, which accelerates adoption and daily use for engineering teams.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Choosing Linear when stakeholders need heavy customization, large ecosystem apps, or mature reporting.</description>
        <reason>Linear's opinionated design is a liability when teams need workflow customization that Linear does not support out of the box.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-friendliness">
      <list>
        <item>Jira: REST v3 + GraphQL alpha; full CRUD; JQL for queries. Best for complex query-driven workflows.</item>
        <item>Linear: GraphQL-first; fast; excellent pagination. Best for engineering-metric automation.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects v2: GraphQL; free; tightly coupled to repo events. Best for code-adjacent workflows.</item>
        <item>GitLab: REST + GraphQL; self-host option; webhook-driven. Best for DevOps-integrated automation.</item>
        <item>Azure DevOps: REST + OData Analytics; enterprise auth. Best for Microsoft-stack traceability pipelines.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="requirements-phase">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every Must-Have requirement must have a stakeholder quote or measured pain point as evidence; requirements without evidence are downgraded to Should-Have.</statement>
        <rationale>Evidence-anchored MoSCoW prevents post-selection disputes ("I said we needed X"). It also forces specificity that reveals when requirements conflict.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply hard constraints first (price ceiling, data residency, compliance certification, IDP/SCIM support) to reduce the universe to 3-5 candidates before evaluating features.</statement>
        <rationale>Compliance posture (SOC2, ISO 27001, HIPAA, FedRAMP, GDPR data residency) can flip the entire shortlist; evaluating features before checking compliance wastes effort.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="poc-evaluation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Time-box the POC to two weeks using actual project data, not sample data; longer evaluation causes decision fatigue without proportional insight.</statement>
        <rationale>Real data surfaces integration gaps, performance issues, and UX friction that demo data hides. Two weeks is sufficient for most team-size decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Include "do nothing" as a baseline option in the ADR with quantified cost of staying on the current tool.</statement>
        <rationale>Without the baseline, the recommendation reads as "we must switch" rather than "switching is better than staying by X%."</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>POC driven only by API scenarios without any UI testing.</description>
        <reason>API success does not predict UI adoption. One Playwright test per shortlisted vendor covering the most common UI flow catches issues that break real adoption.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="scoring-and-adr">
      <rule>
        <statement>Score with weights and run sensitivity analysis; if the winner changes under plus-or-minus 20% weight perturbations, the choice is fragile and requires deeper investigation.</statement>
        <rationale>A fragile winner means requirements are genuinely contested. Surface this before commitment rather than discovering it post-implementation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Quantify migration cost (data ETL, automations, integrations, training, parallel-run period) in the ADR — typically 30-50% of year-1 TCO.</statement>
        <rationale>Migration cost is the most underestimated factor in tool selection and the most common source of post-decision regret.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="ADR: PM Tool Selection">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# ADR: PM Tool Selection — [Date]

## Decision
Adopt Linear for the engineering org (Jira remains for compliance projects).

## Context
Team of 45 engineers; GitHub-first; previous Jira instance at 180 custom fields.

## Requirements (MoSCoW)
### Must
- GitHub PR linking (evidence: @eng-lead, transcript offset 142)
- Sub-$15/user/month (evidence: budget doc Q3)

## Scoring (1-5 scale, weighted)
| Criterion | Weight | Linear | Jira | ClickUp |
|-----------|--------|--------|------|---------|
| UX speed  | 0.30   | 5      | 2    | 3       |
| GitHub    | 0.25   | 5      | 4    | 3       |
| Reporting | 0.20   | 2      | 5    | 4       |
| Price     | 0.25   | 4      | 3    | 4       |
| **Total** |        | **4.1**| **3.4** | **3.5** |

## Sensitivity: ranking stable under ±20% weight perturbation.

## Migration cost estimate
Data: 12,000 issues. Automations: 34 rules. Training: 45 people.
Parallel run: 4 weeks. Total: ~$28k one-time.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>requirements-distiller (sonnet) — distill stakeholder transcripts into MoSCoW with verbatim quote evidence.</item>
        <item>vendor-shortlister (haiku) — apply hard constraints; return shortlist with explicit rejection reason per filtered vendor.</item>
        <item>poc-runner (haiku, calls tool APIs) — drive scripted POC scenarios in trial instances and record latency and success.</item>
        <item>scoring-agent (sonnet) — apply weights, compute totals, run sensitivity analysis under ±20% perturbation.</item>
        <item>decision-writer (opus) — produce ADR with risks, mitigations, migration plan outline.</item>
        <item>pricing-tracker (haiku, scheduled) — monitor vendor pricing pages and update comparison with date stamp.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are requirements-distiller. Inputs: meeting_transcript.md, prior_tools.md.
Emit a MoSCoW table: { "must": [...], "should": [...], "could": [...],
"wont": [...] }. Each item: { "id": "R-NN", "name": "...", "evidence": [
{"quote": "...", "speaker": "...", "transcript_offset": ...} ], "metric":
"...|null" }. Refuse to invent requirements without an evidence quote.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are scoring-agent. Inputs: requirements.json, weights.json,
vendor_findings/*.json. For each vendor, compute weighted score; return
top 3 + sensitivity table showing ranking under ±20% weight perturbations.
Highlight any item where rank flips under sensitivity.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using LLM training knowledge for current feature availability or pricing tiers.</description>
        <reason>Vendor pricing pages and tier names change quarterly. Require evidence from trial instance or dated changelog, never from LLM priors.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting compliance attestations from a badge or marketing page.</description>
        <reason>SOC2, ISO27001 badges without the actual audit report are unverifiable. Require signed security questionnaire (SIG Lite or CAIQ) before shortlisting.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Letting an agent submit an RFP response or sign a DPA.</description>
        <reason>Procurement actions with legal consequences require human authorization. Agents produce drafts only.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <rule>
        <statement>Human-in-the-loop checkpoints are mandatory at: MoSCoW finalization, shortlist approval, POC scope, final pick, and ADR signoff.</statement>
        <rationale>Each checkpoint represents a decision gate where errors compound exponentially downstream.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>jira-cli, glab, gh, linear (community), azdo — Drive POC scenarios per tool</item>
        <item>httpie / curl — Quick REST checks during evaluation</item>
        <item>jq / yq — Manipulate JSON/YAML evaluation artifacts</item>
        <item>pandoc — Render the comparison + ADR to PDF for procurement</item>
        <item>mermaid-cli — Render decision-tree / scoring radar</item>
        <item>dvc / git-lfs — Version artefacts (transcripts, POC outputs)</item>
        <item>mkdocs / mdbook — Publish the evaluation as a navigable site</item>
        <item>playwright — Drive UI-only flows where APIs are missing</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Jira (SaaS) — REST + JQL. Most customizable; complex; ecosystem.</item>
        <item>Linear (SaaS) — GraphQL. Fast, opinionated, GitHub-first.</item>
        <item>ClickUp (SaaS) — REST. All-in-one; deep customization; some perf.</item>
        <item>Notion (SaaS) — REST. Docs + light PM.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects v2 (SaaS) — GraphQL. Free for OSS, integrated with code.</item>
        <item>GitLab (SaaS/OSS) — REST + GraphQL. Full DevOps; self-host option.</item>
        <item>Azure DevOps (SaaS) — REST. Microsoft shops; SAFe templates.</item>
        <item>Trello (SaaS) — REST. Simple kanban; light PM.</item>
        <item>Asana (SaaS) — REST. Marketing/ops slant; goals + portfolios.</item>
        <item>Monday.com (SaaS) — GraphQL. Visual; expensive at scale.</item>
        <item>Smartsheet (SaaS) — REST. Gantt + PPM heritage.</item>
        <item>Wrike (SaaS) — REST. Enterprise PM with proofing/marketing slant.</item>
        <item>Targetprocess / Apptio (SaaS) — REST. SAFe/portfolio.</item>
        <item>Hansoft (On-prem/SaaS) — REST. Game/aerospace heritage.</item>
        <item>OpenProject / Redmine / Tuleap / Plane (OSS) — REST. Self-hosted alternatives.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Anchor evaluation to actual workflows, not feature checklists. A 1-hour pilot of a real epic + sprint beats a week of spec-reading.</item>
        <item>MoSCoW with evidence; no Must without a stakeholder quote or measured pain point.</item>
        <item>Two-week time-box for POC; longer == decision-fatigue.</item>
        <item>Score with weights + sensitivity; if the winner flips under reasonable weight changes, the choice is fragile.</item>
        <item>Always include "do nothing" as a baseline option in the ADR.</item>
        <item>Quantify migration cost (data, automations, integrations, training, parallel-run period) — frequently 30–50% of year-1 TCO.</item>
        <item>Procurement: get vendor security questionnaires (SIG Lite, CAIQ) signed; do not assume marketing claims.</item>
        <item>Check IDP/SCIM and SSO before features; failing here forces re-platforming.</item>
        <item>Check egress: full data export, automation export, custom-field export. Lock-in proportional to import-only support.</item>
        <item>Check rate limits and webhook reliability — agent-driven workflows find these limits fast.</item>
        <item>Document the decision (ADR) with date, weights, scoring matrix; re-review annually.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/requirements-doc.md" purpose="Stakeholder-interview questions and MoSCoW requirements matrix template."/>
      <template path="templates/poc-runner.py" purpose="Minimal POC scenario harness that drives scripted tasks against any REST-enabled PM tool."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/learning/library"/>
      <link href="https://adr.github.io/"/>
      <ref slug="pm-tools-comparison"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
